message.content:
First, we need to calculate the quick assets. Quick assets include the most liquid assets, which in this case are:
 • Cash on Hand
 • Bank Deposits
 • Interest Receivable
 • Accounts Receivable

Note that Inventory is not included.

Step 1. List the End Amounts for these accounts:
 Cash on Hand: -1,980,427.60
 Bank Deposits: 385,137.69
 Interest Receivable: 18,176.52
 Accounts Receivable: 12,792,007.89

Step 2. Sum the quick assets:
 Quick Assets = (-1,980,427.60) + 385,137.69 + 18,176.52 + 12,792,007.89

Calculate step by step:
 a. (-1,980,427.60) + 385,137.69 = -1,595,289.91
 b. -1,595,289.91 + 18,176.52 = -1,577,113.39
 c. -1,577,113.39 + 12,792,007.89 = 11,214,894.50

Step 3. Identify the Total Current Liabilities at the end of the period:
 Total Current Liabilities = 1,015,922.54

Step 4. Calculate the Quick Ratio:
 Quick Ratio = Quick Assets / Total Current Liabilities
 Quick Ratio = 11,214,894.50 / 1,015,922.54 ≈ 11.04

Thus, the Quick Ratio at the end of the reporting period is approximately 11.04.

Now, the answer in the required json format is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Quick Ratio": "11.04"
  }
}
